 I apologize for the confusion. Here's an example XML file that conforms to a known schema and uses the GeoJSON file to provide references in the mission plan for things such as GPS location, tree type, etc.:
```php
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<Mission xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance">
    <MissionInformation>
        <TaskDescription>Take pictures of trees at the four corners of the farm</TaskDescription>
    </MissionInformation>
    <Tasks>
        <Task id="1">
            <Location xsi:type="GeoJSONPoint">
                <Latitude>37.36628908556382</Latitude>
                <Longitude>-120.42298051393493</Longitude>
            </Location>
            <Action>Take a picture of the tree at this location</Action>
        </Task>
        <Task id="2">
            <Location xsi:type="GeoJSONPoint">
                <Latitude>37.36626996761184</Latitude>
                <Longitude>-120.42301417901265</Longitude>
            </Location>
            <Action>Take a picture of the tree at this location</Action>
        </Task>
        <Task id="3">
            <Location xsi:type="GeoJSONPoint">
                <Latitude>37.36635678715399</Latitude>
                <Longitude>-120.42299259529793</Longitude>
            </Location>
            <Action>Take a picture of the tree at this location</Action>
        </Task>
        <Task id="4">
            <Location xsi:type="GeoJSONPoint">
                <Latitude>37.366300703749474</Latitude>
                <Longitude>-120.42300386899338</Longitude>
            </Location>
            <Action>Take a picture of the tree at this location</Action>
        </Task>
    </Tasks>
</Mission>
```
Please note that I've used the `xsi:type="GeoJSONPoint"` attribute to indicate that the `Location` element is of type GeoJSONPoint. You may need to adjust this based on your specific schema. 